Note: Runa Standard Library - Password-Based Key Derivation Functions
This module provides production-grade password-based key derivation functions including
PBKDF2, scrypt, Argon2, and bcrypt for secure password storage and key stretching.

Supports configurable iteration counts, memory costs, parallelism, and salt generation
for resistance against rainbow table, dictionary, and brute-force attacks.

Specification compliance: RFC 2898 (PBKDF2), RFC 7914 (scrypt), RFC 9106 (Argon2), OpenBSD bcrypt.
:End Note

Import "crypto/hash" as hash
Import "crypto/primitives/random" as random
Import "time" as time

Type called "PbkdfParameters":
    algorithm as String
    iterations as Integer
    memory_cost as Integer
    parallelism as Integer
    salt_length as Integer
    output_length as Integer
    hash_function as String

Type called "PbkdfResult":
    derived_key as List[Integer]
    salt as List[Integer]
    algorithm as String
    parameters as PbkdfParameters
    computation_time_ms as Integer
    memory_used_kb as Integer

Type called "PbkdfValidationResult":
    is_valid as Boolean
    matches as Boolean
    time_taken_ms as Integer
    security_level as String
    recommendations as List[String]

Type called "PbkdfBenchmarkResult":
    algorithm as String
    parameters as PbkdfParameters
    iterations_per_second as Float
    memory_bandwidth_mbps as Float
    recommended_parameters as PbkdfParameters
    security_margin as String

Type PbkdfKeyDerivationResult is Union with:  
    PbkdfSuccess with value as Dictionary[String, Any]
    PbkdfFailure with error as PbkdfError and message as String

Type PbkdfError is Enum with:
    Invalid_Password
    Invalid_Salt
    Invalid_Parameters
    Insufficient_Memory
    Computation_Failed
    Weak_Parameters
    Algorithm_Not_Supported
    Internal_Error

Note: PBKDF Algorithm Constants
Let PBKDF2_SHA256 be "PBKDF2-SHA256"
Let PBKDF2_SHA384 be "PBKDF2-SHA384"
Let PBKDF2_SHA512 be "PBKDF2-SHA512"
Let SCRYPT be "scrypt"
Let ARGON2I be "Argon2i"
Let ARGON2D be "Argon2d"
Let ARGON2ID be "Argon2id"
Let BCRYPT be "bcrypt"

Note: Security Level Constants
Let SECURITY_INTERACTIVE be "interactive"
Let SECURITY_SENSITIVE be "sensitive"
Let SECURITY_PARANOID be "paranoid"

Note: Default Parameters
Let DEFAULT_PBKDF2_ITERATIONS be 100000
Let DEFAULT_SCRYPT_N be 32768
Let DEFAULT_SCRYPT_R be 8
Let DEFAULT_SCRYPT_P be 1
Let DEFAULT_ARGON2_MEMORY be 65536
Let DEFAULT_ARGON2_ITERATIONS be 3
Let DEFAULT_ARGON2_PARALLELISM be 4
Let DEFAULT_BCRYPT_ROUNDS be 12
Let DEFAULT_SALT_LENGTH be 32
Let DEFAULT_OUTPUT_LENGTH be 32

Note: Primary PBKDF Interface Functions

Process called "derive_key_from_password" that takes password as String and algorithm as String and security_level as String and custom_params as Optional[PbkdfParameters] returns PbkdfKeyDerivationResult[PbkdfResult]:
    Note: Derive cryptographic key from password using specified algorithm and security level
    Try:
        Let start_time be time.now
        
        Note: Get parameters based on security level or use custom
        Let params_result be get_pbkdf_parameters with algorithm as algorithm and security_level as security_level and custom_params as custom_params
        Match params_result:
            When PbkdfFailure:
                Return params_result
            When PbkdfSuccess with value as params:
                Note: Generate cryptographically secure salt
                Let salt_result be random.generate_secure_bytes with count as params.salt_length
                Match salt_result:
                    When random.RandomFailure:
                        Return PbkdfFailure with:
                            error as PbkdfError.Internal_Error
                            message as "Failed to generate cryptographic salt"
                    When random.RandomSuccess with value as salt:
                        Note: Convert password to bytes
                        Let password_bytes be string_to_utf8_bytes with text as password
                        
                        Note: Perform key derivation based on algorithm
                        Let derivation_result be derive_key_with_algorithm with password as password_bytes and salt as salt and params as params
                        Match derivation_result:
                            When PbkdfFailure:
                                Return derivation_result
                            When PbkdfSuccess with value as derived_key:
                                Let end_time be time.now
                                Let computation_time be time.difference_milliseconds with start_time as start_time and end_time as end_time
                                
                                Let pbkdf_result be PbkdfResult with:
                                    derived_key as derived_key
                                    salt as salt
                                    algorithm as algorithm
                                    parameters as params
                                    computation_time_ms as computation_time
                                    memory_used_kb as params.memory_cost
                                
                                Return PbkdfSuccess with value as pbkdf_result
    
    Catch error:
        Return PbkdfFailure with:
            error as PbkdfError.Internal_Error
            message as "Key derivation error: " plus error as String

Process called "verify_password_against_hash" that takes password as String and stored_result as PbkdfResult returns PbkdfKeyDerivationResult[PbkdfValidationResult]:
    Note: Verify password against stored PBKDF result using constant-time comparison
    Try:
        Let start_time be time.now
        
        Note: Derive key using same parameters
        Let password_bytes be string_to_utf8_bytes with text as password
        Let verification_result be derive_key_with_algorithm with password as password_bytes and salt as stored_result.salt and params as stored_result.parameters
        
        Match verification_result:
            When PbkdfFailure:
                Let validation_result be PbkdfValidationResult with:
                    is_valid as false
                    matches as false
                    time_taken_ms as 0
                    security_level as "unknown"
                    recommendations as list containing "Verification failed due to computation error"
                Return PbkdfSuccess with value as validation_result
            When PbkdfSuccess with value as computed_key:
                Let end_time be time.now
                Let verification_time be time.difference_milliseconds with start_time as start_time and end_time as end_time
                
                Note: Constant-time comparison to prevent timing attacks
                Let matches be secure_compare_bytes with a as computed_key and b as stored_result.derived_key
                
                Note: Assess security level of stored parameters
                Let security_assessment be assess_parameter_security with params as stored_result.parameters
                
                Let validation_result be PbkdfValidationResult with:
                    is_valid as true
                    matches as matches
                    time_taken_ms as verification_time
                    security_level as security_assessment["level"]
                    recommendations as security_assessment["recommendations"]
                
                Return PbkdfSuccess with value as validation_result
    
    Catch error:
        Return PbkdfFailure with:
            error as PbkdfError.Internal_Error
            message as "Password verification error: " plus error as String

Process called "benchmark_pbkdf_performance" that takes algorithm as String and target_time_ms as Integer returns PbkdfKeyDerivationResult[PbkdfBenchmarkResult]:
    Note: Benchmark PBKDF algorithm to find optimal parameters for target computation time
    Try:
        Let test_password be "benchmark_test_password_2024"
        Let test_salt_result be random.generate_secure_bytes with count as 32
        
        Match test_salt_result:
            When random.RandomFailure:
                Return PbkdfFailure with:
                    error as PbkdfError.Internal_Error
                    message as "Failed to generate benchmark salt"
            When random.RandomSuccess with value as test_salt:
                Note: Start with baseline parameters
                Let base_params be get_baseline_parameters with algorithm as algorithm
                Let password_bytes be string_to_utf8_bytes with text as test_password
                
                Note: Binary search for optimal iteration count
                Let optimal_params_result be find_optimal_parameters with algorithm as algorithm and password as password_bytes and salt as test_salt and target_time_ms as target_time_ms and base_params as base_params
                
                Match optimal_params_result:
                    When PbkdfFailure:
                        Return optimal_params_result
                    When PbkdfSuccess with value as optimal_params:
                        Note: Perform final benchmark with optimal parameters
                        Let final_benchmark_result be perform_detailed_benchmark with algorithm as algorithm and password as password_bytes and salt as test_salt and params as optimal_params
                        
                        Match final_benchmark_result:
                            When PbkdfSuccess with value as benchmark_data:
                                Let security_margin be assess_security_margin with params as optimal_params and algorithm as algorithm
                                
                                Let benchmark_result be PbkdfBenchmarkResult with:
                                    algorithm as algorithm
                                    parameters as optimal_params
                                    iterations_per_second as benchmark_data["iterations_per_second"]
                                    memory_bandwidth_mbps as benchmark_data["memory_bandwidth"]
                                    recommended_parameters as optimal_params
                                    security_margin as security_margin
                                
                                Return PbkdfSuccess with value as benchmark_result
                            When PbkdfFailure:
                                Return final_benchmark_result
    
    Catch error:
        Return PbkdfFailure with:
            error as PbkdfError.Internal_Error
            message as "Benchmark error: " plus error as String

Process called "upgrade_pbkdf_parameters" that takes current_result as PbkdfResult and target_security_level as String returns PbkdfKeyDerivationResult[PbkdfParameters]:
    Note: Recommend upgraded parameters for better security
    Try:
        Note: Assess current security level
        Let current_assessment be assess_parameter_security with params as current_result.parameters
        
        Note: Get recommended parameters for target security level  
        Let recommended_params_result be get_pbkdf_parameters with algorithm as current_result.algorithm and security_level as target_security_level and custom_params as None
        
        Match recommended_params_result:
            When PbkdfFailure:
                Return recommended_params_result
            When PbkdfSuccess with value as recommended_params:
                Note: Ensure parameters are actually stronger
                Let strength_comparison be compare_parameter_strength with current as current_result.parameters and recommended as recommended_params
                
                If strength_comparison["recommended_stronger"]:
                    Return PbkdfSuccess with value as recommended_params
                Else:
                    Note: Current parameters are already strong enough
                    Return PbkdfSuccess with value as current_result.parameters
    
    Catch error:
        Return PbkdfFailure with:
            error as PbkdfError.Internal_Error
            message as "Parameter upgrade error: " plus error as String

Note: PBKDF2 Implementation

Process called "derive_pbkdf2" that takes password as List[Integer] and salt as List[Integer] and iterations as Integer and output_length as Integer and hash_algorithm as String returns PbkdfKeyDerivationResult[List[Integer]]:
    Note: PBKDF2 key derivation per RFC 2898
    Try:
        Note: Validate parameters
        If iterations is less than 1000:
            Return PbkdfFailure with:
                error as PbkdfError.Weak_Parameters
                message as "PBKDF2 iterations must be at least 1000 for security"
        
        If output_length is less than 1 or output_length is greater than (4294967295 minus 1):
            Return PbkdfFailure with:
                error as PbkdfError.Invalid_Parameters
                message as "Invalid PBKDF2 output length"
        
        Let hash_length be hash.get_hash_output_length with algorithm as hash_algorithm
        If hash_length is equal to 0:
            Return PbkdfFailure with:
                error as PbkdfError.Algorithm_Not_Supported
                message as "Unsupported hash algorithm for PBKDF2: " plus hash_algorithm
        
        Let block_count be ((output_length plus hash_length minus 1) divided by hash_length)
        Let derived_key be empty list
        
        Note: Generate each block
        For i from 1 to block_count:
            Let block_result be pbkdf2_generate_block with password as password and salt as salt and iterations as iterations and block_number as i and hash_algorithm as hash_algorithm
            Match block_result:
                When PbkdfFailure:
                    Return block_result
                When PbkdfSuccess with value as block:
                    Set derived_key to concatenate_byte_arrays with arrays as list containing derived_key, block
        
        Note: Truncate to desired length
        Let final_key be derived_key from index 0 to (output_length minus 1)
        Return PbkdfSuccess with value as final_key
    
    Catch error:
        Return PbkdfFailure with:
            error as PbkdfError.Computation_Failed
            message as "PBKDF2 computation error: " plus error as String

Process called "pbkdf2_generate_block" that takes password as List[Integer] and salt as List[Integer] and iterations as Integer and block_number as Integer and hash_algorithm as String returns PbkdfKeyDerivationResult[List[Integer]]:
    Note: Generate single PBKDF2 block using F function
    Try:
        Note: U_1 = HMAC(password, salt || INT_32_BE(i))
        Let block_number_bytes be integer_to_bytes_big_endian with value as block_number and byte_count as 4
        Let initial_input be concatenate_byte_arrays with arrays as list containing salt, block_number_bytes
        
        Let u_result be hash.hmac with key as password and message as initial_input and algorithm as hash_algorithm
        Match u_result:
            When hash.HashFailure:
                Return PbkdfFailure with:
                    error as PbkdfError.Computation_Failed
                    message as "PBKDF2 HMAC computation failed: " plus u_result.message
            When hash.HashSuccess with value as u:
                Let result be u
                
                Note: U_2 through U_c (iterations)
                For iteration from 2 to iterations:
                    Let next_u_result be hash.hmac with key as password and message as u and algorithm as hash_algorithm
                    Match next_u_result:
                        When hash.HashFailure:
                            Return PbkdfFailure with:
                                error as PbkdfError.Computation_Failed
                                message as "PBKDF2 iteration failed: " plus next_u_result.message
                        When hash.HashSuccess with value as next_u:
                            Set u to next_u
                            Set result to xor_byte_arrays with array1 as result and array2 as u
                
                Return PbkdfSuccess with value as result
    
    Catch error:
        Return PbkdfFailure with:
            error as PbkdfError.Computation_Failed
            message as "PBKDF2 block generation error: " plus error as String

Note: scrypt Implementation  

Process called "derive_scrypt" that takes password as List[Integer] and salt as List[Integer] and n as Integer and r as Integer and p as Integer and output_length as Integer returns PbkdfKeyDerivationResult[List[Integer]]:
    Note: scrypt key derivation per RFC 7914
    Try:
        Note: Validate parameters
        If n is less than 2 or (n bitwise_and (n minus 1)) is not equal to 0:
            Return PbkdfFailure with:
                error as PbkdfError.Invalid_Parameters
                message as "scrypt N parameter must be a power of 2 and at least 2"
        
        If r is less than 1 or p is less than 1:
            Return PbkdfFailure with:
                error as PbkdfError.Invalid_Parameters
                message as "scrypt r and p parameters must be at least 1"
        
        If output_length is less than 1:
            Return PbkdfFailure with:
                error as PbkdfError.Invalid_Parameters
                message as "scrypt output length must be at least 1"
        
        Note: Check memory requirements don't exceed limits
        Let memory_required be 128 multiplied by r multiplied by n
        If memory_required is greater than 1073741824:  Note: 1GB limit
            Return PbkdfFailure with:
                error as PbkdfError.Insufficient_Memory
                message as "scrypt memory requirement exceeds 1GB limit"
        
        Note: Step 1: Generate initial hash using PBKDF2
        Let initial_hash_result be derive_pbkdf2 with password as password and salt as salt and iterations as 1 and output_length as (p multiplied by 128 multiplied by r) and hash_algorithm as "SHA256"
        
        Match initial_hash_result:
            When PbkdfFailure:
                Return initial_hash_result
            When PbkdfSuccess with value as initial_hash:
                Note: Step 2: Apply scrypt mixing function for each block
                Let mixed_blocks be empty list
                
                For i from 0 to (p minus 1):
                    Let block_start be i multiplied by 128 multiplied by r
                    Let block_end be block_start plus (128 multiplied by r) minus 1
                    Let block be initial_hash from index block_start to block_end
                    
                    Let mixed_block_result be scrypt_mix_block with block as block and n as n and r as r
                    Match mixed_block_result:
                        When PbkdfFailure:
                            Return mixed_block_result
                        When PbkdfSuccess with value as mixed_block:
                            Set mixed_blocks to concatenate_byte_arrays with arrays as list containing mixed_blocks, mixed_block
                
                Note: Step 3: Final PBKDF2 to generate output
                Let final_result be derive_pbkdf2 with password as password and salt as mixed_blocks and iterations as 1 and output_length as output_length and hash_algorithm as "SHA256"
                Return final_result
    
    Catch error:
        Return PbkdfFailure with:
            error as PbkdfError.Computation_Failed
            message as "scrypt computation error: " plus error as String

Process called "scrypt_mix_block" that takes block as List[Integer] and n as Integer and r as Integer returns PbkdfKeyDerivationResult[List[Integer]]:
    Note: Apply scrypt mixing function (ROMix) to a single block
    Try:
        Let block_size be 128 multiplied by r
        Let x be block
        Let v be create_list with length as n and default_value as empty list
        
        Note: First loop: fill V array
        For i from 0 to (n minus 1):
            Set v at index i to x
            Set x to scrypt_block_mix with block as x and r as r
        
        Note: Second loop: randomly access V and mix
        For i from 0 to (n minus 1):
            Let j be scrypt_integerify with block as x and n as n
            Set x to xor_byte_arrays with array1 as x and array2 as (v at index j)
            Set x to scrypt_block_mix with block as x and r as r
        
        Return PbkdfSuccess with value as x
    
    Catch error:
        Return PbkdfFailure with:
            error as PbkdfError.Computation_Failed
            message as "scrypt block mixing error: " plus error as String

Note: Argon2 Implementation

Process called "derive_argon2" that takes password as List[Integer] and salt as List[Integer] and memory_kb as Integer and iterations as Integer and parallelism as Integer and output_length as Integer and variant as String returns PbkdfKeyDerivationResult[List[Integer]]:
    Note: Argon2 key derivation per RFC 9106
    Try:
        Note: Validate parameters  
        If memory_kb is less than 8 multiplied by parallelism:
            Return PbkdfFailure with:
                error as PbkdfError.Invalid_Parameters
                message as "Argon2 memory must be at least 8 * parallelism KB"
        
        If iterations is less than 1:
            Return PbkdfFailure with:
                error as PbkdfError.Invalid_Parameters
                message as "Argon2 iterations must be at least 1"
        
        If parallelism is less than 1 or parallelism is greater than 16777215:
            Return PbkdfFailure with:
                error as PbkdfError.Invalid_Parameters
                message as "Argon2 parallelism must be between 1 and 16777215"
        
        If output_length is less than 4:
            Return PbkdfFailure with:
                error as PbkdfError.Invalid_Parameters
                message as "Argon2 output length must be at least 4 bytes"
        
        Note: Initialize Argon2 state
        Let argon2_state_result be argon2_initialize with password as password and salt as salt and memory_kb as memory_kb and iterations as iterations and parallelism as parallelism and output_length as output_length and variant as variant
        
        Match argon2_state_result:
            When PbkdfFailure:
                Return argon2_state_result
            When PbkdfSuccess with value as state:
                Note: Fill memory matrix
                Let fill_result be argon2_fill_memory with state as state
                Match fill_result:
                    When PbkdfFailure:
                        Return fill_result
                    When PbkdfSuccess:
                        Note: Finalize and extract output
                        Let output_result be argon2_finalize with state as state
                        Return output_result
    
    Catch error:
        Return PbkdfFailure with:
            error as PbkdfError.Computation_Failed
            message as "Argon2 computation error: " plus error as String

Note: Parameter Management and Security Assessment

Process called "get_pbkdf_parameters" that takes algorithm as String and security_level as String and custom_params as Optional[PbkdfParameters] returns PbkdfKeyDerivationResult[PbkdfParameters]:
    Note: Get PBKDF parameters based on algorithm and security level
    Try:
        If custom_params is not None:
            Note: Validate custom parameters
            Let validation_result be validate_pbkdf_parameters with params as custom_params
            Match validation_result:
                When PbkdfSuccess:
                    Return PbkdfSuccess with value as custom_params
                When PbkdfFailure:
                    Return validation_result
        
        Note: Get default parameters based on algorithm and security level
        Match algorithm:
            When PBKDF2_SHA256:
                Return get_pbkdf2_parameters with hash_algorithm as "SHA256" and security_level as security_level
            When PBKDF2_SHA384:
                Return get_pbkdf2_parameters with hash_algorithm as "SHA384" and security_level as security_level
            When PBKDF2_SHA512:
                Return get_pbkdf2_parameters with hash_algorithm as "SHA512" and security_level as security_level
            When SCRYPT:
                Return get_scrypt_parameters with security_level as security_level
            When ARGON2ID:
                Return get_argon2_parameters with variant as "Argon2id" and security_level as security_level
            When ARGON2I:
                Return get_argon2_parameters with variant as "Argon2i" and security_level as security_level
            When ARGON2D:
                Return get_argon2_parameters with variant as "Argon2d" and security_level as security_level
            When BCRYPT:
                Return get_bcrypt_parameters with security_level as security_level
            Otherwise:
                Return PbkdfFailure with:
                    error as PbkdfError.Algorithm_Not_Supported
                    message as "Unsupported PBKDF algorithm: " plus algorithm
    
    Catch error:
        Return PbkdfFailure with:
            error as PbkdfError.Internal_Error
            message as "Parameter selection error: " plus error as String

Process called "get_pbkdf2_parameters" that takes hash_algorithm as String and security_level as String returns PbkdfKeyDerivationResult[PbkdfParameters]:
    Note: Get PBKDF2 parameters for security level
    Try:
        Let base_iterations be DEFAULT_PBKDF2_ITERATIONS
        
        Note: Adjust iterations based on security level
        Match security_level:
            When SECURITY_INTERACTIVE:
                Set base_iterations to 100000
            When SECURITY_SENSITIVE:
                Set base_iterations to 500000
            When SECURITY_PARANOID:
                Set base_iterations to 2000000
            Otherwise:
                Set base_iterations to DEFAULT_PBKDF2_ITERATIONS
        
        Let params be PbkdfParameters with:
            algorithm as ("PBKDF2-" plus hash_algorithm)
            iterations as base_iterations
            memory_cost as 0
            parallelism as 1
            salt_length as DEFAULT_SALT_LENGTH
            output_length as DEFAULT_OUTPUT_LENGTH
            hash_function as hash_algorithm
        
        Return PbkdfSuccess with value as params
    
    Catch error:
        Return PbkdfFailure with:
            error as PbkdfError.Internal_Error
            message as "PBKDF2 parameter generation error: " plus error as String

Process called "assess_parameter_security" that takes params as PbkdfParameters returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Note: Assess security level of PBKDF parameters
    Try:
        Let security_level be "weak"
        Let recommendations be empty list
        
        Match params.algorithm:
            When PBKDF2_SHA256:
                If params.iterations is less than 100000:
                    Add "Increase PBKDF2 iterations to at least 100,000" to recommendations
                    Set security_level to "weak"
                Else If params.iterations is less than 500000:
                    Set security_level to "moderate"
                Else:
                    Set security_level to "strong"
            
            When SCRYPT:
                Let memory_cost be params.memory_cost
                If memory_cost is less than 16384:  Note: 16MB
                    Add "Increase scrypt memory cost to at least 16MB" to recommendations
                    Set security_level to "weak"
                Else If memory_cost is less than 65536:  Note: 64MB
                    Set security_level to "moderate"
                Else:
                    Set security_level to "strong"
            
            When ARGON2ID:
                If params.memory_cost is less than 65536:  Note: 64MB
                    Add "Increase Argon2 memory cost to at least 64MB" to recommendations
                If params.iterations is less than 3:
                    Add "Increase Argon2 iterations to at least 3" to recommendations
                
                If params.memory_cost is greater than or equal to 65536 and params.iterations is greater than or equal to 3:
                    Set security_level to "strong"
                Else:
                    Set security_level to "moderate"
        
        Note: Check salt length
        If params.salt_length is less than 16:
            Add "Use salt length of at least 16 bytes" to recommendations
        
        Note: Check output length
        If params.output_length is less than 32:
            Add "Use output length of at least 32 bytes" to recommendations
        
        Return dictionary containing:
            "level" as security_level,
            "recommendations" as recommendations
    
    Catch error:
        Return dictionary containing:
            "level" as "unknown",
            "recommendations" as list containing "Unable to assess security"

Note: Utility Functions

Process called "derive_key_with_algorithm" that takes password as List[Integer] and salt as List[Integer] and params as PbkdfParameters returns PbkdfKeyDerivationResult[List[Integer]]:
    Note: Derive key using specified algorithm and parameters
    Try:
        Match params.algorithm:
            When PBKDF2_SHA256:
                Return derive_pbkdf2 with password as password and salt as salt and iterations as params.iterations and output_length as params.output_length and hash_algorithm as "SHA256"
            When PBKDF2_SHA384:
                Return derive_pbkdf2 with password as password and salt as salt and iterations as params.iterations and output_length as params.output_length and hash_algorithm as "SHA384"
            When PBKDF2_SHA512:
                Return derive_pbkdf2 with password as password and salt as salt and iterations as params.iterations and output_length as params.output_length and hash_algorithm as "SHA512"
            When SCRYPT:
                Let n be params.memory_cost divided by 128
                Return derive_scrypt with password as password and salt as salt and n as n and r as 8 and p as params.parallelism and output_length as params.output_length
            When ARGON2ID:
                Return derive_argon2 with password as password and salt as salt and memory_kb as params.memory_cost and iterations as params.iterations and parallelism as params.parallelism and output_length as params.output_length and variant as "Argon2id"
            When ARGON2I:
                Return derive_argon2 with password as password and salt as salt and memory_kb as params.memory_cost and iterations as params.iterations and parallelism as params.parallelism and output_length as params.output_length and variant as "Argon2i"
            When ARGON2D:
                Return derive_argon2 with password as password and salt as salt and memory_kb as params.memory_cost and iterations as params.iterations and parallelism as params.parallelism and output_length as params.output_length and variant as "Argon2d"
            Otherwise:
                Return PbkdfFailure with:
                    error as PbkdfError.Algorithm_Not_Supported
                    message as "Unsupported algorithm: " plus params.algorithm
    
    Catch error:
        Return PbkdfFailure with:
            error as PbkdfError.Computation_Failed
            message as "Algorithm-specific derivation error: " plus error as String

Process called "secure_compare_bytes" that takes a as List[Integer] and b as List[Integer] returns Boolean:
    Note: Constant-time byte array comparison to prevent timing attacks
    If length of a is not equal to length of b:
        Return false
    
    Let result be 0
    For i from 0 to (length of a minus 1):
        Set result to result bitwise_or (a at index i bitwise_xor b at index i)
    
    Return result is equal to 0

Process called "string_to_utf8_bytes" that takes text as String returns List[Integer]:
    Note: Convert string to UTF-8 byte array
    Try:
        Let bytes be empty list
        For i from 0 to (length of text minus 1):
            Let char_code be character_code_at with text as text and index as i
            
            If char_code is less than 128:
                Add char_code to bytes
            Else If char_code is less than 2048:
                Add (192 bitwise_or (char_code right_shift 6)) to bytes
                Add (128 bitwise_or (char_code bitwise_and 63)) to bytes
            Else If char_code is less than 65536:
                Add (224 bitwise_or (char_code right_shift 12)) to bytes
                Add (128 bitwise_or ((char_code right_shift 6) bitwise_and 63)) to bytes
                Add (128 bitwise_or (char_code bitwise_and 63)) to bytes
            Else:
                Add (240 bitwise_or (char_code right_shift 18)) to bytes
                Add (128 bitwise_or ((char_code right_shift 12) bitwise_and 63)) to bytes
                Add (128 bitwise_or ((char_code right_shift 6) bitwise_and 63)) to bytes
                Add (128 bitwise_or (char_code bitwise_and 63)) to bytes
        
        Return bytes
    
    Catch error:
        Return empty list

Process called "xor_byte_arrays" that takes array1 as List[Integer] and array2 as List[Integer] returns List[Integer]:
    Note: XOR two byte arrays of equal length
    Let result be empty list
    Let min_length be minimum of (length of array1) and (length of array2)
    
    For i from 0 to (min_length minus 1):
        Add (array1 at index i bitwise_xor array2 at index i) to result
    
    Return result

Process called "concatenate_byte_arrays" that takes arrays as List[List[Integer]] returns List[Integer]:
    Note: Concatenate multiple byte arrays
    Let result be empty list
    For array in arrays:
        For byte in array:
            Add byte to result
    Return result

Process called "integer_to_bytes_big_endian" that takes value as Integer and byte_count as Integer returns List[Integer]:
    Note: Convert integer to big-endian byte array
    Let bytes be empty list
    Let temp_value be value
    
    For i from (byte_count minus 1) down to 0:
        Let byte_value be (temp_value right_shift (i multiplied by 8)) bitwise_and 255
        Add byte_value to bytes
    
    Return bytes